Got it - that's a real constraint. The thing is, the mobile app is a client that connects to a backend server. You can't run the backend on Android itself, so we need the backend running somewhere accessible from your phone.

Two practical paths:

Option 1: Deploy to the cloud (best for testing on mobile) Deploy the backend to a free service like Heroku or Railway so it's live and accessible from your phone anywhere. The mobile app points to the cloud URL instead of localhost. Takes about 10 minutes to set up. Once deployed, your phone can connect to it no matter where you are.

Option 2: Tunnel from your computer (when you're near it) Use ngrok to expose your local backend to the internet with a public URL. Then your phone can reach it. But this only works when your computer is running the backend.

For smooth mobile development, I'd push you toward Option 1 - deploy to the cloud now. Then you can test everything on your phone immediately without waiting for your computer. The backend code is already production-ready.

